<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO CHARLES</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jan  6  7:07:31 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Charles,<br><br>
I am going to try to be short and to the point.<br><br>
I don't get my information from left wing tracts. I recommend Neil Sheehan's book which I mentioned above. It is there that you will find his mention of Diem's, Communist Denunciation Campaign. In the same section Sheehan talks of how Diem misread the pride his own people had in the Viet Minh. It was borne of the knowledge that Asians who were made inferior by a hundred years of colonial rule had cause to feel pride because they had defeated their European &quot;masters&quot;. Of course, Diem wouldn't be aware of this sense of pride or feeling - he sat out the war.<br><br>
While your arguments concerning your experience in NY city in 1972, the germ warfare, Cuba, etc are compelling, though adding to the length of your post, they do nothing to disprove the existence of a Communist Denunciation Campaign - which was instituted by Diem and gave summary powers to province chiefs to murder suspected communists.<br><br>
I find it interesting that you say you are not trying to &quot;defend Diem&quot;.<br><br>
As for the French Union. Ho Chi Minh allowed Vietnam to become part of the French Union in 1946 - well before the Battle Of Dien Bien Phu that you mention.<br><br>
His decision came about because of his abandonment by the US after WWII, in which he was the top intelligence officer for the OSS in VN. Ho loved the Americans he worked with; so much so, that he patterned the Declaration of Independence of the Democratic Republic of VN - after the US Declaration of Independence! The US ignored his entreaties to recognize his government, AS DID THE SOVIET UNION! Ho was left no choice but to allow the French back in - because he feared domination by the CHINESE. His insistence on Vietnam remaining *one country* caused the French to begin to plot his downfall by coup d' etat. War, *which he did not want*, broke out shortly thereafter. Source: Karnow's _History Of Vietnam_.<br><br>
It is interesting, your reference to the French Union. Algerian troops, also members of the French Union, fought the Viet Minh at DBP. The French Union was another name for the French Empire.<br><br>
As far as your reference to fear of a monolitic takeover by communist powers during that time, and our subsequent policy of containment, you are correct. It is also typical of the disregard that the world leaders, at that time, had for a native people to determine their own destiny.
